WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.640
Algorithmic bias encodes prejudice into machines, a phenomenon known as the New Jim Code.

00:00:06.640 --> 00:00:09.960
But how does math actually learn to be racist?

00:00:09.960 --> 00:00:14.760
People assume technology is objective, but designers quietly bake human blind spots into

00:00:14.760 --> 00:00:16.320
the architecture.

00:00:16.320 --> 00:00:21.000
Take the commercial facial analysis software developed by major companies like IBM and

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:22.120
Microsoft.

00:00:22.120 --> 00:00:27.560
To learn what a human face looks like, an AI ingests a massive library of reference photos,

00:00:27.560 --> 00:00:29.600
called a benchmark data set.

00:00:29.600 --> 00:00:33.000
The system has no independent concept of a human face.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:37.880
It can only recognize the specific mathematical patterns present in the photos it was fed.

00:00:37.880 --> 00:00:40.600
And researchers uncovered a critical flaw.

00:00:40.600 --> 00:00:44.960
These standard data sets were overwhelmingly composed of lighter-skinned subjects.

00:00:44.960 --> 00:00:49.960
In fact, up to 86% of the reference images featured lighter-skinned people.

00:00:49.960 --> 00:00:54.800
Because of this skewed data, the trained AI effortlessly and accurately identifies lighter-skinned

00:00:54.800 --> 00:00:59.560
males, but it struggles to find a mathematical match for darker-skinned females, resulting

00:00:59.560 --> 00:01:02.480
in error rates of nearly 35%.

00:01:02.480 --> 00:01:07.840
Sociologist Ruha Benjamin calls this the New Jim Code, when discriminatory design hides

00:01:07.840 --> 00:01:10.620
behind a cloak of algorithmic objectivity.

00:01:10.620 --> 00:01:15.080
So when a commercial facial recognition system misidentifies a person in the real world,

00:01:15.080 --> 00:01:19.840
and flags them as a risk, it isn't an accidental glitch, it's engineered in equity.
